gojomo@... wrote:

&gt;Prasenjit Mukherjee wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;Is there a way to figure out the domains(or WorkQueues) which are 
&gt;&gt;completed(rather exhausted) ?
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Programmatically, or as a crawl operator seeking a summary report?
&gt;
&gt;If the latter, there are not-yet-documented query-string parameters
&gt;that may be added to the Frontier report URL to (1) select a non-default
&gt;Frontier report format to use; and (2) request that the report be dumped
&gt;to a file rather than to the browser.
&gt;
&gt;Specifically:
&gt;
&gt;* the &#39;name&#39; parameter may be specified as &#39;nonempty&#39; or &#39;all&#39;. Each
&gt;   of these non-default formats reports one queue per line, and does
&gt;   not truncate the lists after a few thousand, like the default
&gt;   report does. Thus, in a large crawl, they can take a while to dump.
&gt;   As the names suggest, &#39;all&#39; shows all queues -- even those that
&gt;   have been exhausted -- and &#39;nonempty&#39; only those with items remaining.
&gt;   A legend explaining each field of the single-line display will
&gt;   appear at top.
&gt;* the &#39;dumpFile&#39; parameter may give the name of file, relative to the
&gt;   crawler working directory, to which to dump the report rather than
&gt;   to the browser.
&gt;
&gt;So for example, the following URL...
&gt;
&gt;   http://localhost:8080/reports/frontier.jsp?name=all&dumpFile=frontier-all.report
&gt;
&gt;...would dump the queue-per-line all-queues Frontier report to the
&gt;file &#39;frontier-all.report&#39; in the working directory in which
&gt;the crawler was launched.
&gt;
&gt;Someday, UI controls to reach these options will be added.
&gt;
&gt;Keep in mind that a queue can be temporarily exhausted -- with more
&gt;URLs to be discovered from offsite inlinks right around the corner.
&gt;This might even be quite common early in crawls, if a few lone
&gt;resources are referenced from a site before reaching its own
&gt;interlinked content.
&gt;
&gt;Hope this helps,
